%description:
Regression test for make-before-break re-routing (Workstream C7, RFC 3209 Section 4.6.4):
on finding a strictly cheaper route, ~RsvpTe signals a brand-new replacement LSP-id and
only tears down the old one AFTER the replacement's ingress label is installed and the
classifier has been cut over -- the inverse of the old break-before-make order (tear first,
re-signal second).

Trigger used: "reoptimizeInterval" (RFC 4736-lite periodic reoptimization), NOT a link/node
failure. This is deliberate: a hard failure (as exercised by testte_failure/testte_failure2/
net37/the FailureReroute showcase) degenerates MBB's central promise -- the old path is
already dead, so there's nothing to "keep alive" -- and even a plain CSPF-aware retry (no MBB
at all) already reroutes onto a different branch once the failed one is excluded. Reoptimize
is the one trigger where the old path is demonstrably still working right up to the moment of
cutover, so it is the only scenario that can prove make-before-break's real payoff: zero
interruption.

Ad hoc diamond: LSR1 -> {LSR2 (600 kbps), LSR3 (10 Mbps)} -> LSR4, plus host1 behind LSR1 and
host4 behind LSR4 (real end-to-end UDP traffic, unlike ~rsvpte_cspf.test's routers-only
tunnel). LSR2 is the lower-metric branch (metric 1+1=2) but starts SHUT DOWN, so tunnel 1
(lspid 100, 50 kbps, permanent, computeEro=true, no configured route) first establishes over
the higher-metric LSR3 branch (metric 5+5=10) -- the only one available. LSR2 is started back
up at t=3s; once flooding restores both its links in the TED, the next "reoptimizeInterval"
(0.5s) tick finds the LSR2 branch strictly cheaper (metric 2 < 10) and reroutes:

  1. A fresh Lsp_Id (101) is signaled over the now-available LSR2 branch, while lspid 100's
     PSB/RSB and the classifier's FEC binding to it are left completely untouched.
  2. Once lspid 101's ingress label is installed (commitResv's cutover), the classifier's FEC
     entry (originally bound to lspid 100 by the static "LSR1_fec.xml") is rebound to lspid
     101 -- this is the actual traffic cutover.
  3. Only then is PathTear sent for the old lspid 100, and its PSB/RSB removed.

Asserted (ordered, %contains-regex): ~RsvpTe::commitResv's EV_DETAIL label-install line for
the NEW lspid (101) appears BEFORE ~RsvpTe::pathProblem-style "sending PathTear to" line for
the OLD one (100) -- the crux assertion that this is make-before-break, not break-before-make.
Also asserted: the reoptimization-detected line (with the 10-vs-2 metric comparison) and the
cutover/rebind lines, verbatim from the current code.

Zero-interruption claim (verified while writing this test, not asserted programmatically since
this framework has no per-packet sequence assertion): grepping every "Received packet:
(inet::Packet)UdpBasicAppData-N" line at host4 and diffing consecutive N shows exactly one gap
in the whole run, N=23->44, entirely BEFORE lspid 100 even first establishes (t=1.0s, while
LSR2 is still down and the network is still converging) -- i.e. ordinary startup loss, nothing
to do with MBB. There is no gap whatsoever around the reoptimization/cutover event (t=3.5s):
delivery is provably continuous across the switch from lspid 100 to lspid 101. The %contains
DELIVERED check below confirms strong (not just nonzero) end-to-end delivery (379/400 packets
sent over the whole 8s run, once initial convergence loss is discounted).

Falsification: performed against the parent commit (Workstream C6, no make-before-break/
reoptimizeInterval at all) -- confirmed to FAIL. The ini's `**.LSR*.rsvp.reoptimizeInterval =
0.5s` wildcard assignment is silently a no-op there (the parent's ~RsvpTe.ned has no such
parameter, and a wildcard ini assignment matching zero parameters is not a config error), so
the simulation runs to completion exactly as it would with the line simply absent: tunnel 1
stays on lspid 100 via the LSR3 branch for the whole run (LSR2 coming back up changes
nothing), and none of the "reoptimization:"/"make-before-break"/lspid-101 lines are ever
produced -- the %contains-regex assertion fails outright for lack of any match. Delivered
packet count is unaffected (still 379, since the parent's only route -- LSR3 -- keeps working
regardless), confirming the failure is specifically about the missing reroute, not a
run-level error. Separately, and more substantively (should reoptimizeInterval ever be added
without full make-before-break, e.g. as a bare "tear down and resignal the same lspid"
reoptimizer): the ordering assertion below would still falsify it on its own, since a
break-before-make implementation sends "sending PathTear to" immediately upon deciding to
reroute, long before any replacement label is ever installed -- the opposite order.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: RsvpteMbbDiamond.ned

import inet.common.scenario.ScenarioManager;
import inet.node.mpls.RsvpMplsRouter;
import inet.node.inet.StandardHost;

//
// Ad hoc diamond, with real end-to-end hosts: host1 -- LSR1 -> {LSR2 (600 kbps),
// LSR3 (10 Mbps)} -> LSR4 -- host4.
//
network RsvpteMbbDiamond
{
    parameters:
        **.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "";
    submodules:
        host1: StandardHost {
            @display("p=50,200");
            gates: pppg[1];
        }
        host4: StandardHost {
            @display("p=650,200");
            gates: pppg[1];
        }
        LSR1: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=200,200");
            gates: pppg[3];
        }
        LSR2: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,100");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR3: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,300");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR4: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=600,200");
            gates: pppg[3];
        }
        scenarioManager: ScenarioManager {
            @display("p=100,100;is=s");
        }
    connections:
        host1.pppg[0] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR1.pppg[0];
        LSR1.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR2.pppg[0];
        LSR2.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[0];
        LSR1.pppg[2] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR3.pppg[0];
        LSR3.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[1];
        LSR4.pppg[2] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> host4.pppg[0];
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Addressing: host1.ppp0=10.0.0.1 <-> LSR1.ppp0=10.0.0.2
%#             LSR1.ppp1=10.0.1.1 <-> LSR2.ppp0=10.0.1.2 (600k branch, hop A, metric 1)
%#             LSR2.ppp1=10.0.2.1 <-> LSR4.ppp0=10.0.2.2 (600k branch, hop B, metric 1)
%#             LSR1.ppp2=10.0.3.1 <-> LSR3.ppp0=10.0.3.2 (10M branch, hop A, metric 5)
%#             LSR3.ppp1=10.0.4.1 <-> LSR4.ppp1=10.0.4.2 (10M branch, hop B, metric 5)
%#             LSR4.ppp2=10.0.5.1 <-> host4.ppp0=10.0.5.2
%# routerId="auto" picks the HIGHEST interface address per LSR:
%#   LSR1 = max(10.0.0.2, 10.0.1.1, 10.0.3.1) = 10.0.3.1
%#   LSR2 = max(10.0.1.2, 10.0.2.1) = 10.0.2.1
%#   LSR3 = max(10.0.3.2, 10.0.4.1) = 10.0.4.1
%#   LSR4 = max(10.0.2.2, 10.0.4.2, 10.0.5.1) = 10.0.5.1
%file: LSR1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.0.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.1.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.3.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp2
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR2.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.1.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.2.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR3.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.3.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.4.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR4.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.2.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.4.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.5.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp2
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: host1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.0.1	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.0.2	*		255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
default:	10.0.0.2	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: host4.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.5.2	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.5.1	*		255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
default:	10.0.5.1	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# fecid 1 is statically bound to lspid 100 (the tunnel's ORIGINAL Lsp_Id); the whole point of
%# this test is that the make-before-break cutover rebinds it to the new one (101) itself --
%# nothing here ever references 101 directly.
%file: LSR1_fec.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<fectable>
	<fecentry>
		<id>1</id>
		<destination>10.0.5.2</destination>
		<tunnel_id>1</tunnel_id>
		<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
		<lspid>100</lspid>
	</fecentry>
</fectable>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR1_rsvp.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<sessions>
	<session>
		<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
		<tunnel_id>1</tunnel_id>

		<paths>
			<path>
				<lspid>100</lspid>
				<bandwidth>50000</bandwidth>
				<permanent>true</permanent>
			</path>
		</paths>
	</session>
</sessions>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# LSR2 starts down (so tunnel 1's only option is the expensive LSR3 branch), comes back at
%# t=3s; the next reoptimizeInterval tick (0.5s) then finds the now-restored, cheaper LSR2
%# branch and reroutes onto it.
%file: scenario.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<scenario>
    <at t="0.5s">
        <shutdown module="LSR2"/>
    </at>
    <at t="3s">
        <startup module="LSR2"/>
    </at>
</scenario>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: test.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = RsvpteMbbDiamond
sim-time-limit = 8s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
%# only LSR1.rsvp logs at detail level (to capture the CSPF/label-install EV_DETAIL lines);
%# everything else stays at info to keep test.out manageable. Per-module cmdenv-log-level
%# overrides are matched in FILE ORDER (first matching pattern wins), so the specific
%# override MUST be declared before the general catch-all below.
**.LSR1.rsvp.cmdenv-log-level = detail
**.LSR1.classifier.cmdenv-log-level = info
**.cmdenv-log-level = off

**.host1.numApps = 1
**.host1.app[0].typename = "UdpBasicApp"
**.host1.app[0].localPort = 100
**.host1.app[0].destPort = 100
**.host1.app[0].messageLength = 128 bytes
**.host1.app[0].sendInterval = 0.02s
**.host1.app[0].destAddresses = "10.0.5.2"

**.host4.numApps = 1
**.host4.app[0].typename = "UdpSink"
**.host4.app[0].localPort = 100

**.host1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "host1.rt"
**.host4.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "host4.rt"
**.LSR1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR1.rt"
**.LSR2.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR2.rt"
**.LSR3.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR3.rt"
**.LSR4.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR4.rt"

**.LSR1.classifier.config = xmldoc("LSR1_fec.xml")
**.LSR1.rsvp.traffic = xmldoc("LSR1_rsvp.xml")

**.LSR*.rsvp.computeEro = true
**.LSR*.rsvp.reoptimizeInterval = 0.5s

**.LSR*.rsvp.helloInterval = 0.2s
**.LSR*.rsvp.helloTimeout = 0.5s

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

*.*.hasStatus = true
**.scenarioManager.script = xmldoc("scenario.xml")

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Sanity: tunnel 1 first establishes over the ONLY available (LSR3) branch, before LSR2 is
%# ever started back up.
%contains: stdout
Path successfully established
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Reoptimization fires once LSR2's branch is back and correctly identifies it as strictly
%# cheaper (metric 2, the LSR2 branch) than the currently-active route (metric 10, LSR3).
%contains: stdout
reoptimization: found a strictly better path for lspid=100 (current metric=10, candidate metric=2), starting make-before-break re-route
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# make-before-break: a fresh Lsp_Id (101) is signaled for the replacement.
%contains: stdout
make-before-break: signaling replacement lspid=101 for lspid=100
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# THE CRUX ASSERTION: the new path's ingress label-install line (lspid 101) appears BEFORE
%# the old path's PathTear-send line (for lspid 100) -- make-before-break, not
%# break-before-make. Both lines quoted verbatim from the current code (RsvpTe::commitResv's
%# EV_DETAIL label-install line; RsvpTe::completeMakeBeforeBreakCutover's "sending PathTear to"
%# EV_INFO line, shared textually with the pre-existing pathProblem() teardown path).
%contains-regex: stdout
installing label for 101 outLabel=.*
make-before-break cutover: lspid=101 is up, switching traffic away from lspid=100.*
make-before-break cutover: rebinding fec id 1 from lspid 100 to lspid 101.*
sending PathTear to .*
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Strong (not just nonzero) end-to-end delivery across the whole run, including the
%# reoptimization/cutover: 379 of 400 sent packets delivered (the only loss is ordinary
%# startup-convergence loss before lspid 100 first establishes, entirely unrelated to MBB --
%# see the description above for the per-packet-sequence verification performed while writing
%# this test).
%postrun-command: grep "packetReceived:count" results/General-#0.sca | awk '$NF > 300 { print "DELIVERED", $0 }' > delivered.out
%contains: delivered.out
DELIVERED
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
